### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

localize

### Description

When using i18n it seems extremely difficult to handle the actual hosting part. We have this scenario:

- foo.com/en has the compiled i18n version of the `en` locale
- foo.com/sv has the compiled i18n version of the `sv` locale
- foo.com has an Express proxy server `server.proxy.mjs` that creates a route for `/en` and `/sv`:

```
import { app as appEN } from './server/en/server.mjs';
import { app as appSV } from './server/sv/server.mjs';

server.use('/en', appEN());
server.use('/sv', appSV());
```

There are two main problems I've encountered when trying to get this to work:

1. Including the proxy file for compilation
2. Writing it to `dist/apps/public` instead of `dist/apps/public/browser/<locale>` using the glob pattern in `targets.build.options.assets` will lead to an error saying you're not allowed to write to files outside of the output path

I briefly looked at the `targets.build.options.scripts` but that seems more for external third party scripts that would normally go inside the `<head>` tag.

What I've been forced into doing is have a `server.proxy.mjs` file that I have to copy over with a separate script after the build is done, that I can then start in Docker with `CMD ["node", "./dist/apps/public/server.proxy.mjs"]`.

There are pretty obvious cons here:

- No type safety
- Having to use a separate script entirely just to copy over the file to the dist
- Having import statement to each locale's compiled server app like `import { app as appSV } from './server/sv/server.mjs';` that doesn't exist before you build, in order to set up a route for it using `server.use('/sv', appSV());`, so using a `.ts` file doesn't work even if you were to get the rest of the file to compile.

There are likely more that I've encountered and forgotten at this point.

I've also tried to manually compile this with tools like `tsc` and `esbuild` but I cannot do so without getting error after error or completely wrong outputs in the dist folder.

I feel like it shouldn't have to be this painful to make i18n work with SSR when you require a proxy.

### Proposed solution

Since the problem is not one thing, but rather several, the solution must take this into consideration.

It would be really nice if I could have this inside `angular.json`:

```
  "name": "public",
  ...
  "i18n": {
    "sourceLocale": "en",
    "locales": {
      "sv": "apps/public/src/i18n/sv.json"
    }
  },
  "targets": {
    "build": {
      "options": {
        "i18nProxyServer": "apps/public/server.proxy.ts" // Perhaps this could even be inside the "i18n" field as a "proxyServer" field instead
        ...
      }
    }
  }
```

This would do two things:
1. Include `apps/public/server.proxy.ts` for compilation
2. _Somehow_ give access to the correct import statement for each locale in order to create the route. Ideally you would be able to call a method imported from `@angular/localize` that could give you this information, or something that could be replaced at build time similar to how `$localize.locale` works. Something that would allow you to do like:

```
  // geti18nImports would already know what project it is, and where to look in dist folder
  import { geti18nImports } from '@angular/localize';

  // Would return something like [{ code: 'en', importPath: () => import('./server/en/server.mjs').default }]
  const allLocales = geti18nImports();

  // From here you can simply loop over each locale and create a route for it
  for (const locale of allLocales) {
    server.use(`/${locale.code}`, await locale.importPath());
  }
```

or with the `$localize.locale` methodology:

```
server.use('/en', await $localize.importPath('en').default);
server.use('/sv', await $localize.importPath('sv').default);
```

### Alternatives considered

None in terms of solutions to the proxy problem. But we've also considered having a country select page at foo.com that can link to each locale, but since that's also extremely difficult to do with i18n without creating an entirely separate application, we've been forced out of that option.

I struggle to see any alternative solutions to the problems mentioned, but I'm hoping to hearing what the team's thought around this topic is.

I've seen comments in the past that this is more related to hosting rather than the framework, but if the framework doesn't allow you to host the application(s) in a clean and streamlined way, I think that's problem that needs urgent solving.

I am open to hearing alternative solutions from the team, whether about a new solution entirely or a way to go about this that already exists.
